column37: EVENT_NARRATIVE
column38: EPISODE_NARRATIVE

Heavy rains toward the end of December sent several rivers, including the Ohio and Mississippi Rivers, above flood stage from December into the first part of January. The flooding was minor, consisting mostly of flooded bottomland fields, woodlands, and public park and recreation areas. Some lesser-traveled roads in the bottomlands were flooded. The exception was on the Ohio River at Cairo, where moderate flooding occurred. The river crested at 49.38 feet on the Cairo gage on the 6th. Flood stage at Cairo is 40 feet.

column37: A 45 year-old woman was killed when her vehicle collided head-on with another vehicle on County Highway 2 just west of Minonk in Woodford County during the morning of January 2nd.  Slick roads due to freezing drizzle likely contributed to the crash.
column38: Patchy freezing drizzle occurred across much of north-central Illinois from January 1st through the afternoon of January 2nd.  Thanks to a thin glaze of ice that was deposited, many secondary and untreated roadways became slick and a few traffic accidents subsequently occurred.  One of the accidents resulted in a fatality in rural Woodford County on the morning of January 2nd.

Strong west to northwest winds overspread southeast Illinois behind a cold front. The cold front swept eastward beneath a low pressure center over the Great Lakes region. A peak wind gust to 40 mph was measured at the Carmi airport.

Widespread snow, mixed at times with sleet, spread across southern Illinois during the afternoon hours on January 11th. This was in response to surface low pressure that developed across the Texas and Oklahoma region. This low then moved east-northeastward across the Missouri Bootheel by early evening on the 12th. Warmer temperatures at the surface and aloft gradually changed the precipitation to rain from south to north. The changeover occurred during the overnight hours of the 11th through the morning of the 12th. Sleet was not widespread enough to significantly lower snowfall amounts. The heaviest snowfall amounts from this system were from the Marion/Carbondale area north and west. The highest amount was 7 inches at Pinckneyville (Perry County). Amounts from 4 to 6 inches were the norm from the Marion/Carbondale area up to Mount Vernon. Amounts tapered down to an inch or two along the Ohio River from Cairo to Metropolis. There were significant travel impacts during the evening hours and into the overnight hours, as snow-covered roads led to numerous accidents. Portions of I-57 and I-64 were closed for a period of time in southern Illinois. At least 10 to 15 vehicles slid off roads in Johnson County. Snowfall rates were near an inch per hour during the evening of the 11th in some areas. At Desoto in Jackson County, 3.5 inches fell in three hours.

column37: Several rounds of heavy snow fell across Randolph County beginning during the afternoon hours of January 11th through the midday hours of January 12th. The co-op observation from Steeleville reported a storm total of 7.5 inches with this system.
column38: A strong storm system moved through the region with snow developing by the evening hours of January 11th. The area received several waves of heavy snowfall through the morning hours of January 13th. The heaviest snowfall, which exceeded a foot in some locations, occurred over portions of central/northeast Missouri and west central Illinois, although over 6 inches of snow fell across the majority of eastern Missouri and western Illinois.

column37: Several rounds of heavy snow fell across Monroe County beginning during the afternoon hours of January 11th through the early morning hours of January 13th. A CoCoRaHS site 4.7 miles south of Columbia reported 8.0 inches of snowfall while a site 3.7 miles east northeast of Fults reported 6.1 inches of snowfall with this system.

Snowfall rates were near an inch per hour during the evening of the 11th in some areas. At Desoto in Jackson County, 3.5 inches fell in three hours.

Widespread snowfall in excess of 6 inches occurred along and north of the I-70 corridor...with as much as 12 to 16 inches falling along and southwest of a Macomb to Lincoln line.  The highest observed snowfall total was 16.0 inches just west of Jacksonville in Morgan County.  Numerous traffic accidents occurred due to snow-covered roads.

column37: Weather observers across Schuyler County measured 2 to 4 inches of snow.  In addition, northerly winds gusting 30-35mph created snow drifts of 1-3 feet deep.  As a result, numerous traffic accidents occurred and vehicles became stuck in drifts, especially on rural roads.
column38: Low pressure tracking from central Oklahoma to eastern Kentucky brought wintry precipitation and strong winds to central Illinois from the late evening of January 18th through midday on January 19th.  1 to 3 inches of snow accumulated along and north of the I-72 corridor...with as much as 5-6 inches further northwest across portions of Knox County.  Enough warm air arrived aloft to create some freezing drizzle along I-72: however, ice amounts were minimal.  Despite the wet nature of the snow, strong northerly winds gusting 30-40mph created considerable drifting snow...with drifts as deep as 1-3 feet.  As a result of the drifting snow, numerous traffic accidents occurred and several roads were closed.

Despite the wet nature of the snow, strong northerly winds gusting 30-40mph created considerable drifting snow...with drifts as deep as 1-3 feet.  As a result of the drifting snow, numerous traffic accidents occurred and several roads were closed.

column37: Weather observers across Cass County measured around 2 inches of snow.  In addition, northerly winds gusting 30-35mph created snow drifts of 1-3 feet deep.  As a result, numerous traffic accidents occurred and vehicles became stuck in drifts, especially on rural roads.

A deepening low pressure center tracked from eastern Arkansas across middle Tennessee during the day, then into southeast Kentucky on the evening of the 19th.  As colder air quickly pushed southward, rain changed to snow during the afternoon  hours. Travel impacts were very high due to the combination of high snowfall rates (1 to 2 inches per hour), strong wind gusts of 40 to 50 mph, and rapidly falling temperatures. Roads quickly became snow and ice covered, and visibility was frequently below one-quarter mile for a few hours. Near blizzard conditions were  experienced in many areas for a few hours. There were numerous accidents, and some roads were closed for a while during the heart of the event. I-57 in southern Illinois was among the worst hit, which caused the Illinois State Police to close the interstate from Mount Vernon to Marion on the evening of the 19th. The heaviest snowfall totals were observed along a corridor from the Marion-Carbondale area northeast across Mcleansboro to Mt. Carmel. Widespread snowfall totals of 4 to 6 inches occurred in this corridor, with pockets of 6 to 8 inches from Marion to southwest Hamilton County.  Across the extreme southeast counties of Hardin, Pope, and Massac, snowfall amounts were mainly from 1 to 3 inches. Measuring the snowfall accurately was a challenge due to the strong winds throughout the afternoon and evening hours. Drifting of the snow hindered travel. Convective elements, including thundersnow, produced snowfall rates from one to two inches per hour. Peak wind gusts were measured up to 52 mph at the Carbondale airport and 40 mph at the Carmi airport. Temperatures fell into the mid 20's by the end of the snowstorm, producing wind chills from 10 to 15.

Temperatures fell into the mid 20's by the end of the snowstorm, producing wind chills from 10 to 15.

A deepening low pressure center tracked from eastern Arkansas across middle Tennessee during the day, then into southeast Kentucky on the evening of the 19th.  As colder air quickly pushed southward, rain changed to snow during the afternoon  hours. Travel impacts were very high due to the combination of high snowfall rates (1 to 2 inches per hour), strong wind gusts of 40 to 50 mph, and rapidly falling temperatures. Roads quickly became snow and ice covered, and visibility was frequently below one-quarter mile for a few hours. Near blizzard conditions were  experienced in many areas for a few hours. There were numerous accidents, and some roads were closed for a while during the heart of the event. I-57 in southern Illinois was among the worst hit, which caused the Illinois State Police to close the interstate from Mount Vernon to Marion on the evening of the 19th. The heaviest snowfall totals were observed along a corridor from the Marion-Carbondale area northeast across Mcleansboro to Mt. Carmel. Widespread snowfall totals of 4 to 6 inches occurred in this corridor, with pockets of 6 to 8 inches from Marion to southwest Hamilton County.  Across the extreme southeast counties of Hardin, Pope, and Massac, snowfall amounts were mainly from 1 to 3 inches. Measuring the snowfall accurately was a challenge due to the strong winds throughout the afternoon and evening hours. Drifting of the snow hindered travel. Convective elements, including thundersnow, produced snowfall rates from one to two inches per hour. Peak wind gusts were measured up to 52 mph at the Carbondale airport and 40 mph at the Carmi airport. Temperatures fell into the mid 20's by the end of the snowstorm, producing wind chills from 10 to 15.

column37: A 62 year-old woman was killed when her van skidded off I-155 into the median and rolled over several times.  The woman was driving northbound on I-155 about 3 miles south of IL-136 when she lost control of her vehicle due to icy conditions.  She was ejected from her van and pronounced dead at the scene.
column38: Low pressure approaching from the Southern Plains created areas of freezing drizzle during the morning of January 22nd.  In addition, gusty southeasterly winds ahead of the developing system led to drifting of an existing snow cover.  As a result, scattered slick spots caused numerous traffic accidents...including one that killed a woman on I-155 in Logan County.

Freezing rain and freezing drizzle developed across portions of northern Illinois during the morning of January 22nd and continued into the evening.  The freezing rain mixed with snow at times and transitioned to mainly rain by early Wednesday morning, January 23rd, across parts of the Chicago Metro area but transitioned to mainly snow across northwest Illinois.  A semi slid off Interstate 39 between Rochelle and Rockford during the early afternoon of January 22nd due to the icy conditions.  Ice accumulation amounts included 0.32 inches at the Sugar Grove Airport (ARR); 0.26 inches at the DuPage Airport (DPA); 0.16 inches at O'Hare Airport (ORD); 0.16 inches at Waukegan (UGN); 0.14 inches at the Wheeling Airport (PWK) and 0.04 inches at the Rockford Airport (0.04).  Storm total snow amounts included 5.7 inches at the Rockford Airport; 5.5 inches in Mount Morris; 5.1 inches in Genoa; 5.0 inches one mile southwest of Harvard; 4.5 inches in Highwood; 3.8 inches in McHenry and 1.5 inches at Chicago O'Hare Airport.

column37: Trained spotter reports range from 6.0 inches 1 mile east of Nora to 6.2 inches 2 miles south southeast of Schapville. Cooperative Observer reports ranged from 5.0 inches in Galena to 5.5 inches 3 miles northeast of Stockton.
column38: A significant winter storm system brought hazardous travel conditions to the region the afternoon and evening of Tuesday, Jan. 22, through the morning of Wednesday, Jan. 23.  Freezing drizzle and rain fell for much of the morning and afternoon on Tuesday causing slick roads.  Precipitation quickly changed to snow mainly north of a line from Gladstone, IL, to Priceton, IL.  Snowfall totals of 2 to 6 inches were common over much of eastern Iowa and northwest Illinois.  Rainfall totals over three quarters of an inch were seen over west central and north central Illinois.

Heavy snow fell across much of northern Illinois starting during the evening of January 27th and continuing through the morning of January 28th.  A 75 year old male was struck by a plow truck while snow blowing in Lake County, Illinois and died.  Storm total snowfall amounts included 7.3 inches 2 miles north of Waukegan; 7.0 inches 1.6 miles west of Gurnee; 6.0 inches near Algonquin and 5.8 inches 5 miles northwest of Woodstock.

column37: An 82 year-old man died of hypothermia after falling outside his Marquette Heights home during the afternoon of January 29th.
column38: An Arctic cold front plunged through central Illinois on January 29th, bringing a bitterly cold airmass into the region.  Temperatures bottomed out on the morning of January 30th when readings ranged from 15 below to 25 below zero everywhere north of the I-70 corridor.  Record lows were observed at many sites, including 20 below zero at Peoria, 19 below zero at Lincoln, and a record-tying 14 below zero at Springfield.  In addition, strong northwesterly winds gusting 25-35mph created dangerous wind chill readings of 40 to 50 below zero.  Central Illinois Regional Airport in Bloomington logged their all-time coldest wind chill of 53 below zero on the morning of the 30th.  Winds gradually eased as the day progressed: however, actual air temperatures remained below zero along and north of I-72.  With light winds and fresh snow cover, low temperatures once again fell into the teens below zero by the early morning of January 31st, with Peoria establishing a new record low for the date of 19 below zero.  Temperatures finally warmed above zero by the afternoon of the 31st, but didn't substantially warm until February 1st when readings climbed well into the 20s and lower 30s.||Due to the historic cold outbreak, the governor of Illinois declared a State of Emergency.  Hundreds of schools, colleges, and universities were closed.  Illinois state offices were closed and the postal service cancelled service across much of west-central Illinois.  AMTRAK suspended normal services as well.  A water main leak in downtown Peoria caused the closure of City Hall.  More than 500 customers lost power across portions of Peoria and Tazewell County for several hours on the morning of the 30th...mainly impacting the town of Hopedale.  Illinois State Police transported 21 people from a broken down charter bus on I-55 in extreme southern Sangamon County to a nearby restaurant for warmth.  In addition, frost quakes were reported during the peak of the cold at various locations around central Illinois.||One person died due to cold exposure during this event...an 82 year-old man in Marquette Heights.

column37: A state record low temperature was recorded on January 31st when the Cooperative Observer recorded a low temperature  of -38 degrees Fahrenheit. In addition, the lowest wind chill at the Savanna Airport was -53 at 335 AM on January 30th.
column38: A strong arctic high pressure system brought historic cold to much of the Midwest January 29th through January 31st.  Numerous low temperature records were broken, including all-time record lows at Moline.  A state record low temperature was observed by the Mount Carroll Cooperative Observer on January 31st when they record a low of -38F. In addition, life threatening wind chills were reported with values below -30 degrees for many hours.  Numerous schools, churches, and businesses closed during the arctic outbreak.

column37: Several record cold temperatures were broken at the Moline. Record low temperatures were broken on the 30th and 31st when the low temperatures were -29 and -33 Fahrenheit respectively. The -33 degrees on the 31st also broke the records for lowest temperature at the site ad January as well as the all time record low. A record cold high was recorded on January 30th when Moline had a high of -8 degrees. The lowest wind chill was -52 at 229 AM on January 30th.

Extremely cold air moved across northern Illinois during the evening of January 29th and continued through midday on January 31st.  Air temperatures were below zero for 52 consecutive hours at Chicago O'Hare Airport, making it the 4th longest stretch of hours below zero at Chicago.  Chicago O'Hare set a daily record low of -23 on the morning of January 30th and -21 on the morning of January 31st.  Rockford set their all time record low temperature of -31 on the morning of January 31st, with a low of -25 on the morning of January 30th and -16 on the evening of January 29th.  Air temperatures were below zero for 57 consecutive hours at Rockford Airport, making it the 9th longest stretch of hours below zero at Rockford.||Other low temperatures on the morning of January 31st included: -32 at Sugar Grove (ARR); -31 at Rochelle (RPJ); -29 at West Chicago (DPA); -28 at Barrington; -25 at DeKalb (DKB); -24 at Lansing (IGQ); -23 at Waukegan; -23 at Joliet (JOT) and -22 at Dwight.||The lowest wind chills occurred during the morning of January 30th.  The lowest observed wind chills were -56 at DeKalb; -55 at West Chicago; -54 at Pontiac, Rochelle and Sugar Grove; -53 at Morris, Peru and Romeoville; -52 at Chicago O'Hare and Kankakee; -51 at Chicago Midway, Rockford Airport, Lansing; -50 at Chicago Northerly Island; -48 at Wheeling and -45 at Joliet and Waukegan.

Air temperatures were below zero for 52 consecutive hours at Chicago O'Hare Airport, making it the 4th longest stretch of hours below zero at Chicago.  Chicago O'Hare set a daily record low of -23 on the morning of January 30th and -21 on the morning of January 31st.  Rockford set their all time record low temperature of -31 on the morning of January 31st, with a low of -25 on the morning of January 30th and -16 on the evening of January 29th.  Air temperatures were below zero for 57 consecutive hours at Rockford Airport, making it the 9th longest stretch of hours below zero at Rockford.||Other low temperatures on the morning of January 31st included: -32 at Sugar Grove (ARR); -31 at Rochelle (RPJ); -29 at West Chicago (DPA); -28 at Barrington; -25 at DeKalb (DKB); -24 at Lansing (IGQ); -23 at Waukegan; -23 at Joliet (JOT) and -22 at Dwight.||The lowest wind chills occurred during the morning of January 30th.  The lowest observed wind chills were -56 at DeKalb; -55 at West Chicago; -54 at Pontiac, Rochelle and Sugar Grove; -53 at Morris, Peru and Romeoville; -52 at Chicago O'Hare and Kankakee; -51 at Chicago Midway, Rockford Airport, Lansing; -50 at Chicago Northerly Island; -48 at Wheeling and -45 at Joliet and Waukegan.

Wind chill readings dropped to between minus 10 and minus 20 across most of southern Illinois, except for the southern tip of the state from Metropolis to Cairo. The lowest wind  chill reading at Carbondale was minus 15 degrees. Actual air temperatures were in the single digits above zero. Some places along and north of Interstate 64 briefly dropped below zero. Warming centers were opened for those persons who were unable to heat their residences. Approximately two dozen people took advantage of the warming shelters, possibly due to a power outage in the Herrin and Carterville areas. Arctic high pressure moved southeast into the Missouri Valley, producing a bitterly cold north wind.

column37: A 72 year-old Germantown Hills woman died of hypothermia during the early morning of February 1st.  The woman had gone to her garage the night before, but had not returned to her house after several hours.  Her husband eventually found her in the garage during the morning of the 1st.  She was rushed to the hospital, but pronounced dead when efforts to warm her were unsuccessful.
column38: A 72 year-old woman died of hypothermia during the early morning of February 1st.  While temperatures were slowly rebounding from a record-breaking cold snap in late January, she was exposed for several hours to readings in the single digits and teens.

Minor flooding continued from late January into the first week of February on the Ohio, Wabash, and Little Wabash Rivers. The flooding was minor, consisting mostly of flooded bottomland fields, woodlands, and public park and recreation areas. Some lesser-traveled roads in the bottomlands were flooded. Heavy rain impacted the region shortly after the middle part of January, causing this particular flood wave.

Along and west of a line from Fairfield to Harrisburg to Cairo, dense fog formed late at night and continued through the morning hours. The fog reduced visibility to one-quarter mile or less. High pressure over the middle Atlantic states produced south winds that brought milder air over cold moist ground.

column37: A spotter located 1 mile south southwest of Cordova, Illinois reported  1/2 inch of sleet accumulation.
column38: A winter storm spread freezing rain and sleet across the area during the afternoon and night of Tuesday, February 5th. Ice accumulations of a light glaze to over one quarter inch were found across parts of eastern Iowa, northern and west central Illinois, and far northeast Missouri. Some sleet accumulations amounted to around a half inch.  In addition, some thunderstorms were also observed; some of which produced small hail.

column37: The public, through social media, reported 1/4 to 1/2 inch of sleet accumulation in Freeport, Illinois.

Areas of freezing rain with embedded scattered thunderstorms moved across northern Illinois during the afternoon and evening of February 5th.  Air temperatures were near to slightly below freezing with ice accumulation across much of the area.  The highest ice accumulation amounts were generally along and north of Interstate 88.  The freezing rain intensity of moderate to heavy at times limited how much ice accumulated on surfaces.  Some sleet also mixed in with the freezing rain across far northern Illinois.  Storm total ice accumulation amounts included 0.28 inches at the Waukegan Airport (UGN); 0.25 inches in McHenry; 0.25 inches in Elgin; 0.25 inches in DeKalb; 0.19 inches at the Aurora/Sugar Grove Airport (ARR); 0.14 inches at the DuPage Airport (DPA); 0.13 inches at Rockford Airport (RFD); 0.04 inches at Chicago Executive Airport (PWK) and 0.03 inches at Chicago O'Hare Airport (ORD).  Sleet amounts included 0.8 inches at Rockford Airport and 0.4 inches four miles northwest of Crystal Lake.

The freezing rain intensity of moderate to heavy at times limited how much ice accumulated on surfaces.  Some sleet also mixed in with the freezing rain across far northern Illinois.  Storm total ice accumulation amounts included 0.28 inches at the Waukegan Airport (UGN); 0.25 inches in McHenry; 0.25 inches in Elgin; 0.25 inches in DeKalb; 0.19 inches at the Aurora/Sugar Grove Airport (ARR); 0.14 inches at the DuPage Airport (DPA); 0.13 inches at Rockford Airport (RFD); 0.04 inches at Chicago Executive Airport (PWK) and 0.03 inches at Chicago O'Hare Airport (ORD).  Sleet amounts included 0.8 inches at Rockford Airport and 0.4 inches four miles northwest of Crystal Lake.

column37: Stephenson County emergency management reported a quarter to 0.4 of an inch of ice. This reportedly closed numerous schools and businesses.
column38: A winter storm brought widespread freezing rain, sleet, and rain to the region Thursday morning February, 7th across eastern Iowa, northwest Illinois, and northeast Missouri. This event fell on the heels of another freezing rain event on Feb. 5th.  Slick roads, driveways, and sidewalks were common with numerous accidents on major highways. Ice accumulations between a tenth and two tenths of an inch were common. Some higher ice amounts were reported in Stephenson county in Illinois.  ||Strong winds and cold air were found behind this storm with winds gusting between 35 and 50 mph. This caused many tree limbs to fall due to the weight of the ice. Widespread power line damage occurred in southeast Iowa, and northwest Illinois due to the strong west winds and ice accumulation from both the event on February 5 and the 7th.

column37: At least an inch of water was flowing over Illinois Route 130 in eight different areas between Bone Gap and Parkersburg.
column38: A line of thunderstorms developed early in the morning from western Arkansas into south central Missouri ahead of a strong cold front. This line of storms intensified as it moved east-northeast across the mid Mississippi Valley later in the morning. Some severe weather continued through the midday hours as the line progressed up the lower Ohio Valley. This line of storms was the final round of heavy rain, which capped a very wet couple days that resulted in storm totals of 2 to 4 inches. Isolated higher amounts up to near 5 inches were reported. Isolated flooding was reported in some areas. Although instability was weak, very strong winds aloft facilitated isolated severe storms with damaging winds.

column37: Rainfall amounts of 2.50 to 4.00 inches on a frozen ground resulted in widespread areal flooding in much of Lawrence County on February 7th. Many county roads were flooded and impassable. Parts of State Highways, 1, 33 and 250 were also flooded with mud and rock debris on the roads. Several streets in Lawrenceville were closed due to the flooding. Several rescues were made by first responders; one of which was an elderly person in a home surrounded by water, and multiple motorists who attempted to drive through flooded roads in Lawrenceville.
column38: A series of storm systems tracking along a nearly stationary frontal boundary brought copious amounts of rain to southeast Illinois from February 5th through 7th.  Two to four inches of rain fell along and south of the I-70 corridor...with 3.29 being reported 3 miles west of Birds in Lawrence County.  Since the ground was still frozen, much of the rain flowed into run-off...creating significant rises on area streams and causing flooding of many low-lying spots.  Lawrence County was particularly hard hit, with numerous flooded roads around the county.  An elderly resident was removed from a home surrounded by flood water and multiple vehicles stalled in high water in Lawrenceville.  In addition, mud and rock washed across State Route 33 near Robeson Hills.

column37: Moderate flooding occurred on the Little Wabash River. At the Carmi river gage, the river crested at 33.99 feet on the 15th. Flood stage there is 27 feet. Extensive flooding of low fields occurred in areas near Routes 1 and 14 in and around Carmi. Numerous county roads were inundated.
column38: Moderate to major river flooding developed during the month. After a wet January, the active weather pattern continued into February. Frequent moderate to heavy rain events continued pushing not only the monthly and seasonal precipitation totals higher but also the rivers. The winter of 2018-19 ended up being the fourth wettest winter on record at Paducah, Kentucky, where records go back to 1937. February was the second wettest February on record at Paducah. The monthly rainfall total at Paducah was 10.42 inches. Persistent south to southwest winds aloft brought a steady supply of moisture from the Pacific or the Gulf of Mexico into the region. Fronts that lifted north across the region brought southerly winds and moisture into the lower levels. When the two coincided, areas of very heavy rain occurred. For some locations on the lower Ohio River, it was the highest river stage since the historic 2011 flood. Around 50 homes in the city of Metropolis alone were affected by flooding. The flood crest at Paducah, KY (across from Metropolis) was tied with the 1950 flood for the second highest since the Flood of 1937. The 2011 flood remains the worst flood since the Flood of 1937 at Paducah.

column37: Major flooding occurred on the Ohio River. U.S. Highway 60/62 was closed at the Ohio River bridge to Kentucky. This road serves as a primary link between Kentucky and Illinois. A detour of about 80 miles was required for commuters in the area. The governor of Illinois surveyed the flooded part of the county. There was extensive flooding of low-lying woods, fields, and parks. Through February, the impacts were very similar to the March, 1997 flood. Most of the flood gates were installed at Cairo. Areas not protected by the levee and floodwall system were inundated. The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers installed a high-capacity pump near Urbandale to remove water from heavy rainfall on the protected side of the levee. Since the crop season was not underway, agricultural losses were insignificant. The Ohio River did not crest until March at the Cairo river gage.

column37: Moderate flooding of the Ohio River occurred. At the Shawneetown gage, the river crested at 48.96 feet on February 20. Flood stage there is 33 feet, and moderate flooding begins at 43 feet. The community of Old Shawneetown was threatened, but most of this community has been abandoned since the devastating flood of 2011. Very little if any structural flooding was reported in Old Shawneetown. There was considerable flooding of low-lying agricultural land. Numerous county roads were closed. Backwater flooding extended up the Saline River, affecting low ground from Junction to Equality.

column37: Moderate flooding of the Ohio River occurred. A portion of Illinois Route 1 was closed. There was considerable flooding of low-lying woods and fields. Rural county roads were flooded. A campground at Saline Landing was flooded, and Front Street was flooded in Elizabethtown. There was sandbagging around a few homes in Elizabethtown and Cave-In-Rock. At Rosiclare, Illinois Route 146 was closed leading into town, and water was up along a floodgate. The town of Rosiclare put up the first floodgates in the lowest sections of town. However, little or no property damage occurred in Hardin County. The ferry from Cave-In-Rock to the Kentucky shore suspended operations due to high water.

column37: A prolonged major river flood affected at least 50 homes in Metropolis. At Paducah, across the river from Metropolis, the Ohio River crested at 53.27 feet on the 25th. This was tied with the 1950 flood for the second worst flood since the Flood of 1937. Since 1937, only the flood crest of 2011 was higher. The flood crest reached 60.60 feet in the winter of 1937. Metropolis is not protected by a levee or flood wall, so river floodwater impacted the city directly. Heavy rainfall events combined with backwater from the Ohio River caused widespread flooding along the eastern limits of Metropolis. Numerous roads were closed around the county. In the city of Metropolis, portions of 27 city streets were closed. The governor of Illinois toured the flooded area. The riverboat casino in Metropolis was closed for an extended period of time. Outside the city limits, 17 to 20 additional homes were affected in the county. About six of those homes were flooded. At least three water rescues were conducted. The Red Cross opened a shelter in Brookport. Floodgates were installed around Brookport, blocking access to the city from the east.

Freezing rain developed during the afternoon of February 11th and continued through the morning of February 12th, causing significant ice accumulations across all of northern Illinois.  Damage to tree limbs and power lines were reported in some areas.  Storm total ice accumulations included 0.54 inches in DeKalb; 0.50 inches in Oswego, Plainfield, Bolingbrook and McHenry; 0.50 inches at the Aurora/Sugar Grove Airport (ARR); 0.46 inches at Chicago Midway Airport (MDW); 0.44 inches three miles southwest of Midway Airport; 0.44 inches at Chicago O'Hare Airport (ORD); 0.42 inches at Dupage Airport (DPA); 0.40 inches near Newark; 0.34 inches at Rockford Airport (RFD); 0.25 inches near in Downers Grove, Channahon, Peotone and Manteno and 0.07 inches at Waukegan Airport (UGN).

column37: Weather observers reported ice accumulations of one quarter to one half inch across the northern half of Knox County, including one half inch 4 miles east-northeast of Rio.  Tree limbs were damaged and several power outages occurred due to the ice and 40-45mph wind gusts.
column38: Low pressure tracking from southwest Missouri to west-central Indiana brought a period of freezing rain to north-central Illinois from the evening of February 11th into the early morning of February 12th.  While temperatures were warm enough for rain across much of the area, locations along and north of a Galesburg to Wyoming line hovered just below 32F and experienced freezing rain.  Ice accumulations ranged from one quarter to one half inch...with the highest accumulations focused across far northern Knox County.

column37: Trained spotters in East Dubuque and Nora reported 6.3 inches of snow. Significant blowing and drifting snow was widespread over the area with white out conditions at times lingering through the day of February 12. Power outages from down power lines, power poles, and tree branch damage were widespread.
column38: A winter storm moved from the southern Plains into the Great Lakes Monday, February 11 into Tuesday, February 12, bringing snow, freezing rain and some sleet to the area. Significant snow accumulations of 6 to 9 inches fell across portions of northeast Iowa and far northwest Illinois. Ice accumulations from freezing rain ranged from a light glaze to over a quarter inch; especially in parts of northwest Illinois.||Strong winds between 40 and 50 mph were common across the region on the back side of this system.

column37: Power lines were blown down in Laura.
column38: Deepening low pressure centered over the Great Lakes brought strong westerly winds to central Illinois from the afternoon of February 12th through the early morning of February 13th.  Peak wind gusts reached 40-45mph.  Power lines were blown down in the town of Laura in northwest Peoria County and scattered power outages were reported across the county.

A low pressure system tracked east-northeast from the lower Mississippi Valley to the Carolinas. On the north side of this low, widespread sleet, snow, and freezing rain occurred on the afternoon and evening of the 15th. The heaviest snow accumulations were in Jackson and Williamson counties, including Carbondale and Herrin. Up to 5 inches of snow was measured in Herrin, Murphysboro, and Carbondale, along with some sleet. The precipitation was mostly in the form of freezing rain in the southernmost counties from Cairo to Metropolis, where nearly one-quarter inch of glaze was reported. The icing caused some traffic issues. A single-vehicle accident on Interstate 24 over the Ohio River closed the westbound lanes for a short time. The metal-grating bridge over the Ohio River on U.S. 45 from Brookport to Paducah was closed due to icing. Elsewhere across southern Illinois, the precipitation was mainly sleet and snow. Average accumulations of sleet and snow were generally less than two inches. Specific reports included 2 inches in Ware (Union County), 1.5 inches at West Frankfort (Franklin County), one inch in northern Jefferson County, and one-quarter to one-half inch in Vienna (Johnson County) and Mt. Carmel. A number of accidents were reported due to slippery roads.

Up to 5 inches of snow was measured in Herrin, Murphysboro, and Carbondale, along with some sleet. The precipitation was mostly in the form of freezing rain in the southernmost counties from Cairo to Metropolis, where nearly one-quarter inch of glaze was reported. The icing caused some traffic issues. A single-vehicle accident on Interstate 24 over the Ohio River closed the westbound lanes for a short time. The metal-grating bridge over the Ohio River on U.S. 45 from Brookport to Paducah was closed due to icing. Elsewhere across southern Illinois, the precipitation was mainly sleet and snow. Average accumulations of sleet and snow were generally less than two inches. Specific reports included 2 inches in Ware (Union County), 1.5 inches at West Frankfort (Franklin County), one inch in northern Jefferson County, and one-quarter to one-half inch in Vienna (Johnson County) and Mt. Carmel. A number of accidents were reported due to slippery roads.

Snow fell across northern Illinois from the morning of February 17th through the morning of February 18th.  A mixture of freezing rain and snow developed during the afternoon of February 17th in parts of the Chicago Metro area.  Hospitals in those areas reported a spike in the number of slip and fall related injuries on February 17th with the ice covered by snow in many areas.  Most of the people who were injured were able to be treated and released.  Ice accumulation amounts included 0.09 inches at Dupage Airport (DPA); 0.08 inches at the Aurora/Sugar Grove Airport (ARR); 0.06 inches at the Chicago Executive Airport (PWK) and 0.05 inches at Waukegan Airport (UGN).  The highest snowfall amounts were confined to an area in far northern Illinois and fell over a 24 to 30 hour period.  Those snowfall totals included 8.7 inches two miles north of Buffalo Grove; 8.2 inches one mile northeast of Riverwoods; 7.9 inches two miles south southwest of Genoa; 7.8 inches in Highwood; 7.0 inches one mile northeast of Palatine; 7.0 inches in Wheeling and 6.8 inches in Northbrook.  Chicago O'Hare Airport (ORD) measured 4.9 inches and Rockford Airport (RFD) measured 3.8 inches.

A low pressure system strengthened as it moved northeast into the Great Lakes region. Behind a trailing cold front, west winds gusted from 40 to 55 mph late on the night of the 23rd into the early morning of the 24th. The peak wind gust in southern Illinois was 53 mph at the Carbondale airport. A falling tree damaged a residence in Mount Vernon. An occupant of the residence sustained a minor injury that did not require hospitalization.

column38: A strong storm system brought heavy rain and strong winds to all of eastern Iowa, northwest Illinois and northeast Missouri. On the back side of this storm, high winds swept through the region, with wind gusts over 60 mph common over locations generally along and north of Interstate 80 in Iowa and Illinois. This long period of high winds brought large amounts of blowing snow from over 30 miles away from where it fell in northeast Iowa. Even though it only snowed a very small amount, well under 1 inch in northeast Iowa, this blowing snow became so significant that ground blizzard conditions took place the morning and afternoon of February 24th. North to south roads in Buchanan and Delaware counties in Iowa became impassable due to the blizzard conditions.

Very strong and gusty winds developed during the morning hours of February 24th and continued into the evening hours.  Wind gusts between 55 mph and 65 mph were common during this time period which resulted in numerous tree limbs and power lines being blown down.  Some roof damage and uprooted trees were also reported.  In Will County, a semi truck was blown over near the intersection of Ridge Road and Route 126 and another semi truck was blown over on Interstate 57 at the Peotone exit.  In LaSalle County, a semi truck was blown over on Interstate 39 at mile marker 61, blocking both northbound lanes.  In Kankakee County, an entire gas station canopy was blown over near Bradley.  In Ogle County, part of a roof was blown onto Route 38 near Rochelle.  Peak wind gusts included 64 mph near Bolingbrook, Harvard and at the Aurora/Sugar Grove Airport (ARR); 63 mph three miles east of Antioch; 62 mph in Wheeling; 60 mph at Chicago O'Hare Airport (ORD); 60 mph in Sycamore and at the Peru Airport (VYS); 59 mph at Chicago Midway Airport (MDW); 58 mph at Dupage Airport (DPA) and 58 mph at Morris Airport (C09).

column37: Emergency management reported that flooding occured in the vicinity of Prophetstown and Lyndon along the Rock River due to an ice jam. The flood waters and ice closed a|portion of Highway 78, or Bishop Road, for an extended period of time.
column38: The early afternoon of February 24th, following a heavy rain event, an ice jam formed on the Rock River near Prophetstown, Illinois. Water rose to flood along the river, especially between Prophetstown and Lyndon Illinois through February 27th. The Rock River at Joslin, downstream of the ice jam, hit major flood stage for a few hours the night of February 26th.

column37: Snowmelt, rainwater, and elevated river levels from ice jams in the area, brought the Rock River at Joslin above major flood stage of 16.5 feet, at 5 PM, February 26th. It crested at 16.55 feet, at midnight, February 27th, before falling back below major stage at 7 AM February 27th.

A wintry mix of freezing drizzle, sleet and snow developed during the early morning hours of February 27th across far northern Illinois which created icy conditions.  Numerous cars were reported in ditches along US 20 on the west side of Rockford.

column37: Minor flooding began on the Mississippi River as the month was ending. Low-lying woods and fields not protected by levees were underwater.
column38: The Mississippi River rose above flood stage at the end of the month in response to snowmelt and rain in the northern parts of the river basin.

column37: Major flooding continued on the Ohio River from February into March. At the Cairo river gage, the river crested at 56.51 feet on the 1st. This was just a few inches above the crest of 56.2 feet in the flood of March, 1997. This flood crest was tied with the flood of April, 1975 for the second highest crest since the Flood of 1937. The flood of Spring, 2011 remains the highest crest since 1937. Flood stage at Cairo is 40 feet. U.S. Highway 60/62 was closed at the Ohio River bridge to Kentucky. This road serves as a primary link between Kentucky and Illinois. A detour of about 80 miles was required for commuters in the area. The governor of Illinois surveyed the flooded part of the county. There was extensive flooding of low-lying woods, fields, and parks. The impacts were very similar to the March, 1997 flood. Most of the flood gates were installed at Cairo. Areas not protected by the levee and floodwall system were inundated. The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers installed a high-capacity pump near Urbandale to remove water from heavy rainfall on the protected side of the levee. Since the crop season was not underway, agricultural losses were insignificant.
column38: Moderate to major river flooding during the month of February ended or greatly subsided in March. After a wet January and February, the active weather pattern became quieter in March. The winter of 2018-19 ended up being the fourth wettest winter on record at Paducah, Kentucky, where records go back to 1937. February was the second wettest February on record at Paducah.

column37: Moderate flooding of the Ohio River continued from February into March. A portion of Illinois Route 1 was closed. There was considerable flooding of low-lying woods and fields. Rural county roads were flooded. A campground at Saline Landing was flooded, and Front Street was flooded in Elizabethtown. There was sandbagging around a few homes in Elizabethtown and Cave-In-Rock. At Rosiclare, Illinois Route 146 was closed leading into town, and water was up along a floodgate. The town of Rosiclare put up the first floodgates in the lowest sections of town. However, little or no property damage occurred in Hardin County. Total property damage estimates can be found in the February report. The ferry from Cave-In-Rock to the Kentucky shore suspended operations due to high water.
column38: Moderate to major river flooding during the month of February ended or greatly subsided in March. After a wet January and February, the active weather pattern became quieter in March. The winter of 2018-19 ended up being the fourth wettest winter on record at Paducah, Kentucky, where records go back to 1937. February was the second wettest February on record at Paducah.

column37: Major flooding continued on the Ohio River from February into March. There was extensive flooding of low-lying woods, fields, and parks. The impacts were very similar to the March, 1997 flood. The river crested just a few inches above the flood crest of March, 1997 at the Cairo river gage. The exact crest at Cairo was 56.51 feet on the 1st. Areas not protected by levees were inundated. Since the crop season was not underway, agricultural losses were insignificant. Total property damage estimates can be found in the February report.
column38: Moderate to major river flooding during the month of February ended or greatly subsided in March. After a wet January and February, the active weather pattern became quieter in March. The winter of 2018-19 ended up being the fourth wettest winter on record at Paducah, Kentucky, where records go back to 1937. February was the second wettest February on record at Paducah.

column37: A prolonged major river flood that began in February gradually subsided in March. The flood affected at least 50 homes in Metropolis. The flood crest of 53.27 feet on the Paducah river gage occurred in February. This was tied with the 1950 flood for the second worst flood since the Flood of 1937. More details on the flood crest and on the total property damage estimates can be found in the February report. Metropolis is not protected by a levee or flood wall, so river floodwater impacted the city directly. Heavy rainfall events combined with backwater from the Ohio River caused widespread flooding along the eastern limits of Metropolis. Numerous roads were closed around the county. In the city of Metropolis, portions of 27 city streets were closed. The governor of Illinois toured the flooded area. The riverboat casino in Metropolis was closed for an extended period of time. Outside the Metropolis city limits, 17 to 20 additional homes were affected in the county. About six of those homes were flooded.  The Red Cross opened a shelter in Brookport. Floodgates were installed around Brookport, blocking access to the city from the east.

The winter of 2018-19 ended up being the fourth wettest winter on record at Paducah, Kentucky, where records go back to 1937. February was the second wettest February on record at Paducah.

column37: Moderate flooding of the Ohio River continued from February into March. At the Golconda gage, the river crested at 51.51 feet on February 25. More details on the flood crest and the property damage estimate can be found in the February report. There was considerable flooding of low-lying woods and fields. A few residences in the lowest areas near the river were impacted. Rural Pope County roads were flooded around Brownfield and Hamletsburg.
column38: Moderate to major river flooding during the month of February ended or greatly subsided in March. After a wet January and February, the active weather pattern became quieter in March. The winter of 2018-19 ended up being the fourth wettest winter on record at Paducah, Kentucky, where records go back to 1937. February was the second wettest February on record at Paducah.

column37: Moderate flooding of the Ohio River continued from February into March. At the Shawneetown river gage, the river crested at 48.96 feet on February 20. More details on the February flood crest and the total property damage estimate can be found in the February report. The community of Old Shawneetown was threatened, but most of this community has been abandoned since the devastating flood of 2011. Very little if any structural flooding was reported in Old Shawneetown. There was considerable flooding of low-lying agricultural land. Numerous county roads were closed. Backwater flooding extended up the Saline River, affecting low ground from Junction to Equality.

column37: Minor flooding continued from February into early March on the Mississippi River. Low-lying woods and fields not protected by levees were underwater. The Mississippi River rose above flood stage in response to snowmelt and rain in the northern parts of the river basin.

column37: Moderate flooding on the Wabash River in February ended during the first few days of March. At the New Harmony, IN river gage, the river crested at 20.41 feet on Feb. 16th. Considerable flooding of low ground occurred on the Illinois side of the river. Most of the low ground was dormant agricultural fields. Some county roads were flooded.

Up to two inches of snow fell across southern Illinois. The highest accumulations were from the Marion-Carbondale area east along Route 13 to the Harrisburg area, where 1.5 to two inches of snow fell. There was some sleet mixed with the snow. To the north and south of the Carbondale to Harrisburg corridor, accumulations were mostly an inch or less. The precipitation partially melted on paved surfaces. Travel impacts were light due to the partial melting, as well as the timing of the event during the late night and early Sunday morning hours. A weak low pressure system over the southeastern United States spread moisture northwestward, while Arctic high pressure over the northern Plains funneled cold air into the lower Ohio Valley.

column37: An ice jam occurred one mile downstream of the Dixon Dam and extended upstream to the dam.  Page Drive was closed due to flooding caused by the ice jam.
column38: An ice jam developed along the Rock River near Dixon which caused flooding along portions of the river.

As a low pressure center moved through eastern Kansas, a warm front lifted slowly north into the lower Ohio Valley. Large areas of showers and thunderstorms accompanied this front. A few storms produced hail, including an isolated occurrence of large hail. Heavy rainfall resulted in isolated street flooding.

A low pressure center moved northeast from Kansas to northern Illinois. Strong southwest winds occurred in advance of a cold front that trailed south from the low. The strongest winds occurred in the afternoon and evening hours. Peak measured wind gusts at airport sites were 52 mph at Mount Carmel, 46 mph at Carbondale, 45 mph at Mount Vernon, Cairo, and Carmi, and 43 mph at Harrisburg.

column37: Major river flooding occurred along portions of the Rock River near Bryon.  The river crested at 16.64 feet on March 16th.  Moderate flood stage is 14 feet and major flood stage is 16 feet.  This crest of 16.64 feet was the third highest on record at Bryon.
column38: Heavy rain combined with snow melt caused river levels to reach major stage along portions of the Rock and Pecatonica Rivers during the middle of March.

Throughout the evening of the 13th and all day on the 14th, strong south gradient winds associated with the strong low pressure system gusted up to 55 mph at times. The low pressure center tracked northeast across the Plains to the Great Lakes region. Peak measured wind gusts at airport sites included 59 mph at Carbondale, 55 mph at Mount Carmel, 52 mph at Mount Vernon, 49 mph at Carmi, 48 mph at Harrisburg and Marion, and 46 mph at Metropolis. Part of a metal roof was blown off a building used as a food pantry in Murphysboro, where wind gusts were near 60 mph. In Fairfield in Wayne County, several homes had shingle damage, and a tree was uprooted onto power lines. In Pinckneyville in Perry County, strong winds snapped off a flag pole. Scattered thunderstorms developed ahead of a cold front on the morning of the 14th, producing isolated hail.

column37: The Mississippi River rose above flood stage around mid-month and then continued rising into April. Moderate flooding was in progress by the end of March. There was considerable flooding of low-lying fields and woods and rural county roads. The river crest and its impacts will be contained in the April report.
column38: Rivers began rising again by mid-month as a pair of strong low pressure systems lifted northeast from the Plains to the Great Lakes region. The first system produced widespread heavy rain on the 9th, followed by another heavy rainfall event on the 14th. The flooding on the Mississippi River was enhanced by rapid melting of a record snowpack in the northern states.

column37: The combination of melting snow and heavy rain across the region caused the Rock River near Joslin to rise above major flood stage on March 14th. The river fell below major flood stage on March 24th. The river crested at 18.51 feet on March 16th.
column38: Significant flooding occurred across northwest Illinois during March of 2019.  Moderate to major flooding was observed on Illinois tributary rivers due to snowmelt, saturated soils, and rainfall from March 9th to 12th.  The higher crests occurred on the Rock and Pecatonica Rivers in Illinois during the 2nd and 3rd weeks of March.

column37: The Rock River near Joslin rose above major flood stage of 16.5 feet on March 14th and fell below the major flood stage on March 26th.  The river crested at 18.51 feet.

column37: Major river flooding occurred along portions of the Pecatonica and Rock Rivers during the middle of March.  For the Pecatonica River near Shirland, the river crested at 16.45 feet on March 17th.  Moderate flood stage is 14 feet and major flood stage is 15.5 feet.  For the Rock River at Rockton, the river crested at 14.09 feet on March 17th.  Moderate flood stage is 11 feet and major flood stage is 14 feet.  This crest of 14.09 feet was the fourth highest crest on record at Rockton.  For the Rock River at Latham Park, the river crested at 14.44 feet on March 17th.  Moderate flood stage is 11 feet and major flood stage is 13.5 feet.  This crest of 14.44 feet was the second highest crest on record at Latham Park.  An estimated 700 homes were impacted by flood waters from the Rock River.
column38: Heavy rain combined with snow melt caused river levels to reach major stage along portions of the Rock and Pecatonica Rivers during the middle of March.

column38: Throughout the evening of the 13th and all day on the 14th, strong south gradient winds associated with the strong low pressure system gusted up to 55 mph at times. The low pressure center tracked northeast across the Plains to the Great Lakes region. Peak measured wind gusts at airport sites included 59 mph at Carbondale, 55 mph at Mount Carmel, 52 mph at Mount Vernon, 49 mph at Carmi, 48 mph at Harrisburg and Marion, and 46 mph at Metropolis. Part of a metal roof was blown off a building used as a food pantry in Murphysboro, where wind gusts were near 60 mph. In Fairfield in Wayne County, several homes had shingle damage, and a tree was uprooted onto power lines. In Pinckneyville in Perry County, strong winds snapped off a flag pole. Scattered thunderstorms developed ahead of a cold front on the morning of the 14th, producing isolated hail.

column38: A deep area of low pressure tracking from eastern Nebraska to northern Wisconsin produced very strong gradient winds across central and southeast Illinois on March 14th. As higher momentum air associated with a powerful low-level jet streak mixed to the surface, winds gusted as high as 60-65mph along and south of a Taylorville to Danville line where a High Wind Warning was in effect. Peak measured wind gusts included 67mph at the Lawrenceville Airport, 61mph at Capital Airport in Springfield, and 59mph at the Decatur Airport. Scattered wind damage was reported.

As a strong cold front moved through the region, severe storms developed mainly along and south of Interstate 70. There were numerous reports of large hail, as well as some wind damage and 3 tornadoes.

Multiple thunderstorms developed along and ahead of a cold front in Missouri during the late afternoon. Isolated hail and strong winds accompanied a couple of the storms as they moved east into southern Illinois. Mostly unidirectional wind shear through the vertical profile yielded around 40 to 50 knots of effective bulk shear. An isolated damaging wind event occurred before daytime heating began to wane, stabilizing the atmosphere. After sunset, a small complex of storms trained over the same areas for about an hour. This resulted in locally heavy rain and street flooding.

Lower portions of the Big Muddy River remained above flood stage all month due to backwater from the swollen Mississippi River. At the river gage at Murphysboro, the river crested at 28.07 feet on the 30th. This is just an inch or so above the threshold for moderate flooding. Low-lying woods and fields near the river were flooded, along with sections of a riverfront park.

Prolonged flooding of the Ohio River that began in February continued through the months of March and April. The April flooding was mainly in the Cairo area, extending as far upriver as Grand Chain. Much of the flooding was due to backwater from the swollen Mississippi River. The flooding during April was minor to moderate, which had a considerably smaller impact than the major flooding earlier in the season. The highest river level in April was 49.08 feet on the Cairo river gage. This is still well above the flood stage of 40 feet. Considerable flooding of low-lying woods, fields, and parkland persisted through the month. The river flooding had an increasingly large impact on agricultural interests, since planting season begins in April. However, direct crop losses were still negligible due to the lack of planted crops.

North of the confluence of the Ohio River, the Mississippi River remained above flood stage all month. At the Thebes river gage, the river crested at 39.67 feet on the 5th. Flood stage is 33 feet. This flooding was minor to moderate, which resulted in considerable flooding of low-lying woods and fields. Some county roads were inundated. The flooding increasingly impacted agricultural interests. However, since crop planting was not possible in the flooded areas, there were no direct crop losses at this point in the season.

column37: The Mississippi River remained above its major flood stage of 18 feet through the month of April. The river crested at 20.68 feet on April 8th. Preliminarily this would be the 10th highest crest of record.|On April 29, a man drowned when his car went off Illinois 92 between 18th and 31st Avenues in Rock Island, and into a ditch flooded with water from the Mississippi River. The car was overturned in 6 to 8 feet of water in a normally dry ditch.
column38: The Mississippi River remained high through the month of April due to a combination of snow melt and several rounds of heavy rain. Several points on the river remained above major flood stage through the month.  All locations along the river observed two crests through the month.

A hard freeze was observed across southern Illinois. Low temperatures were in the middle 20's in most areas. Agricultural experts reported some damage to peach buds, but not enough to ruin the peach crop. More than one peach grower reported highly variable peach bud survival, ranging from some trees with no bud survival to other trees with no apparent cold injury. Early crops such as cucumbers were generally unaffected if preventive measures were taken against freeze damage. High pressure from the Ozark Mountains through the Ohio Valley created ideal conditions for frost and freezing temperatures. Winds were light with clear skies.

Early crops such as cucumbers were generally unaffected if preventive measures were taken against freeze damage. High pressure from the Ozark Mountains through the Ohio Valley created ideal conditions for frost and freezing temperatures. Winds were light with clear skies.

column37: The Mississippi River at Burlington remained above its major flood stage of 18 feet for the month of April.
column38: The Mississippi River remained high through the month of April due to a combination of snow melt and several rounds of heavy rain. Several points on the river remained above major flood stage through the month.  All locations along the river observed two crests through the month.

column37: The Mississippi River at Muscatine remained above its flood stage of 20.0 feet from late March and fell back below major flood stage on late in the evening of April 20th. The river crested at 21.9 feet on April 10th.

column37: Minor flooding occurred on the Wabash River. Low-lying woods and fields were inundated, along with a couple of county roads.
column38: The first week of April was dominated by northwest flow aloft and several weak impulses moving southeasterly through the flow. There were a couple rounds of showers and even a few isolated thunderstorms that helped push the Wabash River above flood stage near New Harmony.

column37: The Mississippi River at Dubuque rose above its major flood stage of 20.5 feet at Dubuque Lock and Dam 11 on April 3rd and fell back below the flood stage late in the day on April 9th. column37: Thunderstorm winds blew down several large trees around town and caused minor roof damage to one building.
column38: Scattered strong to severe storms developed across the region. There were numerous reports of large hail and some damaging winds.
Scattered strong to severe storms developed across the region. There were numerous reports of large hail and some damaging winds.

Widespread dense fog blanketed the extreme southern tip of Illinois from Cairo to Metropolis. Visibility was reduced to one-quarter mile or less for several hours. The fog formed just ahead of the leading edge of drier air that was marked by a weak cold front.

A late season winter storm produced heavy snow across portions of northern Illinois with a swath of 5 to 9 inches.  Strong winds gusting to 35 mph and visibility frequently below one half mile produced near blizzard conditions in many areas.  Over 1,000 flights were cancelled at Chicago O'Hare Airport.  Storm total snowfall amounts included 8.5 inches in Woodstock; 8.3 inches near Wonder Lake; 8.0 inches in Sycamore, near Algonquin and 2.5 miles west northwest of Bull Valley; 7.5 inches in De Kalb, Huntley, one mile south of Elburn, one mile south southwest of Lake Villa and six miles northwest of St. Charles; 7.2 inches 2.5 miles west of Elgin; 7.1 inches in McHenry; 7.0 inches in Mendota, two miles northeast of Somonauk and five miles northwest of Woodstock; 6.8 inches in Mundelein and St. Charles; 6.4 inches in La Salle; 6.3 inches in Hebron; 6.1 inches in Earlville; 6.0 inches in Lake Zurich and Crystal Lake and 5.4 inches at Chicago O'Hare Airport (ORD).

column37: A National Weather Service COOP observer reported 8 inches of snow at 11 AM about 1 mile southeast of Princeton, Illinois. Other reports of 5 to 8.5 inches were relayed from the public and spotters in the area.
column38: A storm system tracked into the middle Ohio River Valley during the day on Palm Sunday 2019 (April 14). This brought periods of heavy wet snow to the region during the morning and lasting into the afternoon. Snow fell from northeast Missouri into northeastern Illinois.  The heaviest snow fell in Bureau and Putnam counties where 5 to 8.5 inches of snow were reported.

Areas of frost occurred during the early morning hours as temperatures dipped into the lower 30's. Agricultural experts reported no significant effects on protected crops or  fruit trees. The only reported damage was some minor cold injury that affected random asparagus spears, but there was nothing widespread.  A ridge of high pressure extending from the Gulf coast northward to the lower Ohio and mid Mississippi Valleys provided clear skies and light winds. These conditions were conducive for frost.

The only reported damage was some minor cold injury that affected random asparagus spears, but there was nothing widespread. Scattered strong to severe thunderstorms developed ahead of an advancing cold front during the pre-dawn hours of April 18th.  One storm produced nickel-sized hail in Effingham.

column37: Storms were moving through the region. Several lightning strikes struck a home on Summit View Drive which caused a fire. An 86 year old woman called 911 about the fire and said she was trapped on the second floor of the residence. Firefighters could not get to her in time and she perished in the fire.

Strong winds caused rough conditions on Bangs Lake, an inland lake in Wauconda, IL.  Two boys took a paddle boat onto the lake in the evening and then went into the water.  A 10 year old boy was rescued by nearby fisherman.  Rescue crews later found the body of the other boy who was 9 years old.

The Wabash, Little Wabash, and portions of the Ohio River rose above flood stage late in the month. The flooding was minor, consisting mainly of inundated fields and woodlands in the flood plain. Some county river roads were flooded. Access to river hunting cabins was blocked. A flood gate was installed at Mount Carmel. Oil fields in the flood plain were inaccessible. After a rather dry start to April, the weather pattern turned wetter by mid-month. A series of three heavy rainfall events caused river levels to rise. The first round of heavy rain occurred from the 11th to the 14th, followed by a second round from the 18th to the 20th, and another round from the 23rd to the 25th.

A storm system and its attendant cold front moved across northwest Illinois during the afternoon and evening hours. Showers and thunderstorms developed ahead of this front. A few of these storms became severe. Hail up to the size of quarters fell with these storms as well as wind gusts over 60 MPH. Additionally, over an inch of rain fell in the Quad Cities, which produced brief flash flooding along River Drive in Moline.

column38: A loosely organized cluster of thunderstorms gradually increased due to surface heating ahead of a weak low pressure center over southern Missouri. These storms occurred in a moderately unstable environment, with around 1500 j/kg of cape. Wind shear was relatively weak, however 30 to 35 knots of mid-level flow atop marginal low-level flow resulted in sufficient shear for a weak, brief tornado. Locally heavy rain under the largest storm cluster caused minor road flooding.

column37: River levels continued to run high during the month of April. Heavy rain across the area caused the Mississippi River to rise above its major flood stage of 20.5 feet early in the morning on the 25th, and it remained above its major flood stage into the month of May.  During this second crest, the river crested at 21.77 feet on April 27th.  Preliminarily, this is the 4th highest crest on record at Dubuque Lock and Dam 11.
column38: The Mississippi River remained high through the month of April due to a combination of snow melt and several rounds of heavy rain. column37: A public report of 7 inches of snow in Lena, Illinois was received through social media, including photos of the snow event.
column38: A narrow swath of accumulating wet snow developed on April 27th during the day, and continued into the early evening hours. Most of this snow melted on contact with the ground over northeast Iowa and northern Illinois, but in northern sections of Jo Daviess and Stephenson counties, 4 to 7 inches of snow fell, and accumulated mainly on grass. Despite these snow amounts, the roads were mainly wet to slush covered during the event. However, the heavy snow did result in an extended period of very low visibility and dangerous travel in far northwest Illinois.

column37: A National Weather Service COOP observer reported 6 inches of wet snow accumulation on grassy surfaces, 3 miles north of Stockton, Illinois.

A late season winter storm moved across northern Illinois on April 27th which produced 3 to 6 inches of snow.  Storm total snowfall amounts included 6.0 inches six miles northwest of St. Charles; 5.8 inches three miles north of Campton Hills; 5.5 inches in Belvidere; 5.3 inches 4.6 miles west of Hoffman Estates; 5.1 inches south southwest of Medinah; 5.1 inches 1.6 miles east southeast of Roscoe; 5.0 inches near St. Charles and two miles north northeast of Wheaton; 4.9 inches near Gilberts and in Huntley; 4.8 inches in Palatine; 4.5 inches at Lake Zurich; 4.3 inches in Pingree Grove and one mile north of Bryon; 4.0 inches near Algonquin, Machesney Park, Capron and two miles east of Schaumburg; 3.9 inches in Northbrook; 3.5 inches near South Elgin and near Arlington Heights; 3.3 inches in Round Lake and 3.1 inches in Libertyville.  Storm total snowfall at Rockford Airport (RFD) was 3.7 inches and at Chicago O'Hare Airport (ORD) was 2.5 inches.  Both of these totals were the most snowfall measured at both locations this late in the season.

column37: Several storm chasers witnessed a weak short-lived tornado from different vantage points. The tornado lifted dust from a field and small branches and leaves from a few trees. The location is estimated from a combination of radar and chaser reports. The tornado was rated EF0 with a path length of 1.17 miles and a max path width of 25 yards. There were no deaths or injuries reported with this tornado.

column37: Two feet of standing water was reported in a viaduct on Route 30 near Highland Park Drive.  Route 30 was closed and impassable.  Portions of Highland Park Drive near Hickory Creek were also flooded with several inches of water over the road.
column38: Heavy rain during the afternoon of April 30th lead to flooding across portions for northeast Illinois.

column37: Spotters reported heavy rain and flash flooding in the Springfield metro area and locations to the east toward Buffalo, Rochester and Mechanicsburg during the late evening of April 30th. Rainfall amounts of 2.00 to 3.00 inches on already saturated ground resulted in rapid flash flooding. Numerous streets were closed and vehicles stalled in high water in Springfield, particularly in the eastern and southern parts of the city. The flooding continued past Midnight LST into the early morning hours of May 1st.
column38: Several waves of low pressure tracking along a nearly stationary frontal boundary draped along the I-70 corridor brought heavy rainfall to portions of central Illinois on April 30th.  Widespread amounts of 2.50 to 3.50 were reported along and west of I-55...with the highest amounts in excess of 5 inches concentrated across portions of eastern Mason and western Tazewell counties.  The heavy rain caused flash flooding in Springfield, where numerous roads were closed and at least two vehicles became stranded in rapidly rising water.  Overflowing creeks and water flowing out of farm fields gradually led to areal flooding of several central Illinois communities extending from Scott County northeastward to DeWitt County by May 1st.

column37: Spotters reported heavy rain and flash flooding in the Springfield metro area and locations to the east toward Buffalo, Rochester and Mechanicsburg during the late evening of April 30th. Rainfall amounts of 2.00 to 3.00 inches on already saturated ground resulted in rapid flash flooding. Numerous streets were closed and vehicles stalled in high water in Springfield, particularly in the eastern and southern parts of the city. The flooding continued past Midnight LST into the early morning hours of May 1st. Additional light to moderate rainfall during the early morning hours allowed the flooding to continue into much of May 1st. Local media reported that a road caved in due to the flooding about four miles west of Mechanicsburg shortly after daybreak. The flooding subsided by early afternoon.
column38: Heavy rainfall on April 30th led to areal flooding of many central Illinois communities from Morgan County northeastward to DeWitt County on May 1st.  Overflowing creeks and water flowing out of farm fields caused the closure of numerous roads.  IL-78 just south of the Jacksonville Airport in Morgan County was closed for a time, as were several county roads in Menard and Logan counties.

column37: Minor flooding of the Little Wabash River that began in mid April ended in mid May. Low-lying cropland was flooded, along with some rural county roads.
column38: Several rivers remained above flood stage due to a persistent wet pattern through the winter and spring. May rainfall totals cracked the top five in many locations. At Paducah, KY, 11.09 inches of rain fell, shattering the previous May record by over an inch. In Evansville, IN, 9.15 inches of rain fell, making this the fifth wettest May on record. Normally, 13 to 15 inches of rain falls between March and May. In 2019, however, between 15 and 20 inches of rain was common with some areas receiving between 20 and 25 inches. Paducah experienced its 5th wettest spring on record, with 23.34 inches of rain. Heavy rain was commonplace across most of the Midwest and upper Mississippi Valley, prompting widespread and long lasting flooding throughout the Mississippi, Missouri, and Illinois River basins.

column38: Extensive flooding occurred late May and into June across eastern Iowa, northwest Illinois, and northeast Missouri. Many climate sites only saw 3 days of no precipitation from May 16th to May 31st. |The Wapsipinicon, Iowa, Skunk, Des Moines, Rock, and Green Rivers all recorded a preliminary Top 10 crest on record. column37: Moderate flooding of the Ohio River continued through the month of May. Much of the flooding was due to backwater from the swollen Mississippi River. Due to the lack of planted crops during this extended flood, there was little in the way of direct crop losses.

column37: The Ohio River rose above flood stage at Cairo on February 8 and remained above flood stage through the remainder of the spring. This was the most prolonged flood on the Ohio River at Cairo, IL since records began in the late 1800's. The highest recorded stage in the month of May (2019) was 50.53 feet, which corresponds to the moderate flood category. At this stage, the flooding has a major impact on farming operations in the flood plain, causing some farmers to lose crops. In this prolonged flood, farmers never really had the chance to plant in the flood plain. Flooding of riverside parks and recreational facilities occurred. A few side roads near the river were flooded. Due to the extended duration of the flooding, levees began to show signs of stress. There was concern about the stability of the levees, and seepage became a problem. Some roads nearest the levees began to buckle.

column37: After rising above flood stage in mid-March, the Mississippi River remained above flood stage through the remainder of the spring. At the Thebes river gage, the river crested at 41.83 feet on May 8. However, the river started rising again late in the month. The May crest fell just a little shy of the major flooding category, which starts at 42 feet.  A sewage plant at Thebes was inundated with flood water and was shut down, causing the community to be without sewage services. The Thebes Landing area of town was flooded. There was considerable flooding of low-lying farmland and woods. Some county roads were inundated. Since crop planting was not possible in areas that had been flooded all spring, direct crop losses were not high. Due to the extended duration of the flooding, levees began to show signs of stress. There was concern about the stability of the levees, and seepage became a problem. Some roads nearest the levees began to buckle.

Many climate sites only saw 3 days of no precipitation from May 16th to May 31st. |The Wapsipinicon, Iowa, Skunk, Des Moines, Rock, and Green Rivers all recorded a preliminary Top 10 crest on record. The main stem Mississippi also crested again in late May / early June, with sites from Le Claire LD 14 on downstream recording a Top 10 crest. |Several significant flood events also occurred in March - Early May 2019 due to snowmelt, heavy rain, and saturated soil.

A complex of thunderstorms that developed over northern Illinois dropped southeastward into north-central Indiana during the afternoon of May 16th.  Due to a very unstable airmass feeding into the complex, several supercell thunderstorms developed along its southwestern flank.  These cells skirted across Vermilion County, producing hail as large as baseballs and damaging wind gusts in excess of 60 mph.  The large hail caused nearly 4 million dollars damage to a Toyota dealership in Tilton.

column37: A brief EF-1 tornado hit a farmstead west of Basco in Hancock County Illinois during the evening of May 22nd. A barn was completely destroyed and a large tree was uprooted. The tornado continued for about a half mile before snapping a power pole and then lifting. The tornado was embedded in a larger swath of straight line winds, also estimated around 100 mph, that snapped trees and power poles and damaged outbuildings.

A persistent pattern set up over the Mid Mississippi River Valley during May 21-23. Upper level winds were consistently southwesterly, providing large scale lift and moisture to the area. Converging air along frontal boundaries at the surface provided sufficient low level lift to initial storms each night. During the afternoon of May 22, 2019 specifically, a warm front was moving north into southern Missouri, increasing low level moisture. At the same time a cold front was approaching from the west. Storms developed along the cold front as it pushed southeastward through Missouri. The significant low level wind produced storms favorable for hail and tornadoes.

column38: A persistent pattern set up over the Mid Mississippi River Valley during May 21-23. Upper level winds were consistently southwesterly, providing large scale lift and moisture to the area. Converging air along frontal boundaries at the surface provided sufficient low level lift to initial storms each night. During the afternoon of May 22, 2019 specifically, a warm front was moving north into southern Missouri, increasing low level moisture. At the same time a cold front was approaching from the west. Storms developed along the cold front as it pushed southeastward through Missouri. The significant low level wind produced storms favorable for hail and tornadoes.

column38: An isolated thunderstorm pulsed up to severe levels during the very warm and humid late afternoon hours. A deep layer of southwest winds brought plenty of warm and unstable air into the region. The storm dissipated almost as quickly as it developed.

A slow, south moving cold front and an outflow boundary from morning thunderstorms over northern Missouri and Illinois, combined with a hot and humid environment to produce widespread showers and thunderstorms across portions of eastern Iowa, northwest Illinois and northeast Missouri during the evening and early overnight hours. Several thunderstorms became severe, and produced large hail and damaging winds. Several reports of hail ranging from quarter to golf ball size were reported along and south of Intersate 80, while damaging winds around 60 MPH were reported south of Highway 34. |In addition, torrential rainfall amounts of 1 to 4 inches were reported across southeast Iowa, west central Illinois and northeast Missouri as storms slowly moved across the area. This lead to flash flooding across many major roadways, including Highway 61 near Augusta, IL and Gregory Landing, MO, and County Road A near Rutledge, MO.
